before_annotation.question:
Work your way through the Green-Porter model with price competition and two i.i.d.\ states of demand (no demand or positive demand). Rederive the optimal length of punishment. Show that for a probability $\alpha = \frac{1}{4}$ of no demand, $\delta$ must exceed $\frac{2}{3}$ in order for collusion to be sustainable; show also that at least two periods of punishment are required.

Consider the following infinite-horizon supergame. Two firms choose prices each period. The goods are perfect substitutes and are produced at constant marginal cost $c$, so consumers all buy from the low-price firm; if both firms charge the same price, demand is split equally. In each period there are two possible states of demand: with probability $\alpha$ there is no demand (the ``low-demand state''), and with probability $1-\alpha$ there is positive demand $D(p)$ (the ``high-demand state''). Demand realizations are i.i.d.\ over time. Let $p^m$ denote the monopoly price for unit cost $c$ (i.e.\ $p^m$ maximizes $(p-c)D(p)$), and let $\Pi^m$ denote the monopoly profit in the high-demand state.

Firms do not observe rivals' prices directly, but it is always common knowledge that at least one firm makes no profit in each period. A firm that does not sell cannot tell whether this is due to the low-demand state or to its rival having charged a lower price.

Analyze the following (pure) strategies, which feature a collusive phase and a punishment phase. The game begins in the collusive phase. In the collusive phase, both firms charge $p^m$ until a period in which at least one firm makes zero profit; the occurrence of a zero-profit event is observed by both firms and triggers a punishment phase. In the punishment phase, both firms charge the competitive (Bertrand) price $c$ for exactly $T$ periods (where $T$ is a nonnegative integer, possibly $+\infty$), and then revert to the collusive phase.

Let $V^+$ (respectively, $V^-$) denote the present discounted value of a firm's profits from some date $t$ onward, assuming that at date $t$ the game is in the collusive phase (respectively, starts the punishment phase). By stationarity, $V^+$ and $V^-$ do not depend on time. By definition, these values satisfy
\begin{align}
V^+ &= (1-\alpha)\Bigl(\Pi^m/2 + \delta V^+\Bigr) + \alpha\bigl(\delta V^-\bigr), \tag{6.10}\\
V^- &= \delta^T V^+. \tag{6.11}
\end{align}
In the collusive phase, an undercutting deviation (charging below $p^m$) yields current profit $\Pi^m$ if demand is high and triggers the punishment phase next period; this gives the incentive constraint
\begin{equation}
V^+ \ge (1-\alpha)\bigl(\Pi^m + \delta V^-\bigr) + \alpha(\delta V^-), \tag{6.12}
\end{equation}
which is equivalent to
\begin{equation}
\delta\bigl(V^+ - V^-\bigr) \ge \Pi^m/2. \tag{6.13}
\end{equation}
Equations (6.10) and (6.11) imply
\begin{align}
V^+ &= \frac{(1-\alpha)\Pi^m/2}{1-(1-\alpha)\delta-\alpha\delta^{T+1}}, \tag{6.14}\\
V^- &= \frac{(1-\alpha)\delta^T\Pi^m/2}{1-(1-\alpha)\delta-\alpha\delta^{T+1}}, \tag{6.15}
\end{align}
and substituting (6.14)--(6.15) into (6.13) yields
\begin{equation}
1 \le 2(1-\alpha)\delta + (2\alpha-1)\delta^{T+1}. \tag{6.16}
\end{equation}

(1) Using the fact that the game starts in the collusive phase, formulate the firms' problem as choosing $T$ to maximize $V^+$ subject to (6.16), and rederive the optimal punishment length.

